   <abstract >The Best There Ever Was, The Best There Ever Will Be operates at the intersections of sports and performance studies. This dissertation builds upon Joseph Roach's concept of surrogation, first outlined in 1996's Cities of the Dead, with a primary focus on the performances of four specific players in the sport of basketball: Michael Jordan, LeBron James, Kobe Bryant, and Candace Parker. I argue that each performs Roach's surrogation through media, race, and gender. I also examine the history of women's basketball, arguing that basketball is an inherently gendered sport in both its origins and practices over the course of its evolution in more than a century. The Best There Ever Was, The Best There Ever Will Be uses performance theory, critical race theory, and gender studies to examine how basketball has become a unique performance tradition. First, I analyze a process called mediatization, arguing that Jordan, James, and Bryant's performances of mediatization shape how we think of them in basketball culture. I then examine Jordan's performance as "The Man" of his team and the NBA, using Black masculinity and performativity to create a specific basketball masculinity which James and Bryant surrogate in their own ways. In the third chapter, I pivot to Candace Parker and the WNBA, tracing the history of women's basketball to argue that basketball itself is an inherently gendered sport through both language and the body. I conclude the project by offering up theoretical concepts of possibility and potentiality, drawing these terms from Daniel Sack's After Live to argue that they can help us think deeper about surrogation and basketball. Surrogation is key to analyzing the sport of basketball because basketball itself is its own performance practice, one that will be passed down and endure for future generations.</abstract>
